	Although I understand why SCO shipped it in MS Windows
format (Basically, they're trying to reach more consumers.
I think that's fine.)  This episode shows what the Unix
community is doing wrong and why the MS/Intel combo has been
so successful.

	Basically, the problem is accessibility.  Unix vendors
have not made their products accessible to the general public.
They have failed to make Unix accessible in two fronts.  User
friendliness and product cost.

	For years and years users have complained about Unix
not being user friendly, both at the end user and system
administration levels.  The attitude from the Unix community
has been that there is nothing wrong with it. The user just needs
to spend more time learning it.  Well, this is the wrong attitude.
The most successful businesses listen to what the customers say
and act accordingly ("The customer is always right.")
The Unix community has told the customer "we're right, you're
wrong."  A lot like the U.S. automobile industry before
foreign competition.  With this attitude you only get
alienated and make yourself more inaccessible.

	The cost of commercial Unix packages is outrageous.
The pricing structure pre-dates personal computers.  The time
when companies bought one or two commercial packages, one being
the OS,  and hired and army of programmers to write applications
from them.  At that time the OS was a very important purchase.
Today,  applications are more important because of the large
number of pre-wrapped packages.  Today applications dictate the
OS purchase.  

	With such a high price for a Unix OS the Unix community
see themselves between a rock and a hard place and in a chicken
and the egg dilemma all wrapped into one.  They know
they need to lower the prices to attract more customers
and more importantly developers.  With lower OS costs small developers
have a greater opportunity to succeed because it lowers their
operating costs as well as increases the developer and customer base.
Unfortunately with the current small base of developers and customers
and the dominating foothold that MS/Intel have on the mass market lower
costs would not attract that many customers.  And in the end it will
only reduce profit margins.  The end result is that Unix again becomes
inaccessible to both users and developers.

	When SCO shipped their product directory they wanted to
make it accessible to a large customer based.  They chose MS Windows
because it is widely accessible,  more so than their own product.

	The sad part is that Unix is in a very good position to be
a major player in today's client/server arena.  More so than 
Windows NT is.  Yet,  Unix remains as inaccessible as ever.

	Today I see more and more Unix developers jumping ship
from Unix to (you know what.)  Because they don't see a change
of thinking from the Unix community.


