  I agree with much of what is said by Jay Hauben in his 25th anniversary
of UNIX essay.  But I also think he paints a far too glowing picture of
UNIX.  None of it's down side is examined -- something especially
important at this juncture 25 years after its creation with the market
basically settling in to a Windows/NT and UNIX dichotomy.  Yes, the tool
building approach of UNIX was and is very important, but the foundation is
cracked badly and the gaps are showing up more and more as we try to do
new things.  For some applications it's mind bogglingly difficult to get
them going in an increasingly complex and fractured environment.

  As a simple example, take the following: A library wants to set up a
timer to deal with real-time events but doesn't want to presume on
applications or other libraries by using static global resources like
timers and signal vectors.  What it really wants to do is do the moral
equivalent of ``opening'' or ``mallocing'' a new timer and signal
vector.  The current setup in UNIX for timers and signal vectors is akin
to early Fortran's unit number nonsense.

  Another example is the name space explosion and resulting complexity in
UNIX.  One of UNIX's early touted advantages was that you could open,
read, write and close virtually any resource through the single name space
provided by the file system.  But even at its first inception it already
had other objects and object spaces that had to be accessed in different
ways: the time of day, process state information, etc.  In contrast, Plan
9 from AT&T seems to have corrected much of this.  For instance, by
opening /dev/clock and reding from the handle (file descriptor) to that
object, an application can read the current time of day.

  Or finally, look at the issue of security in UNIX.  Very little thought
was given to it initially (extensive security wasn't even especially
desired).  Now as efforts are made to retrofit better security models into
UNIX, workers are faced with an ill-defined and almost fractal interface
zone between system, applications and users that needs to be defined and
defended.  And the situation is getting worse daily as more and more
software is added with its own individual security needs.

  What's worse, I don't see any prospects for the situation getting better
from either the UNIX camp or Windows/NT -- the two operating systems that
seem destined to dominate our future for the next few years.  UNIX has
turned into a pile of hacks on top of hacks with no real unifying concepts
that draw its disparate parts together.  It has too much invested in
history and compatibility.  On the other hand, Windows/NT has an even
worse history dragging it down.

  Operating systems like Plan 9 from AT&T, the Free Software Foundation's
GNU Hurd and others show some interesting promise but have many obstacles
to acceptance.

  First, there's the bugaboo of compatibility with large masses of already
existing code.  The Hurd will apparently attempt to pass this via a
UNIX/POSIX shell.  When last I looked (around February 1993), Plan 9 seems
to distain the idea of any compatibility with the past.

  Second, there's the issue of production quality: very few people using
UNIX or Windows/NT today for production work are going to be interested in
migrating to an operating system that doesn't offer a rich, robust and
fully documented set of facilities and tools.  Again, when last I looked,
Plan 9 seems dedicated to research goals and very little work had been
done to make it suitable for production work.  The Hurd has a dedicated
small cadre of volunteers working on developing it as a fully endowed
environment, but it's a large task with much work yet to be done.

  Third, there's the issue of benefit: if a new operating system doesn't
differentiate itself from Windows/NT and UNIX in some fundamental way, why
should anyone use it?  The Herd's advertised benefit is that it would be
free.  But this is also its millstone since it gains that freedom via the
GNU ``copyleft'' which prohibits vendors from reselling it and requires
that any changes made to it be given away freely.  Despite the Free
Software Foundation's claims to the contrary, vendors are still very
reluctant to invest effort in a product that they would be forced to give
away to their competitors.

  Plan 9's advertised benefit is that it's amazingly small and much more
self consistent than UNIX.  Rob Pike, the main source of inspiration for
and developer of Plan 9, complains bitterly about the insatiable appetite
of Windows/NT, UNIX and applications for more and more memory and CPU to
drive increasingly complex software.  He claims much of that complexity is
a direct outgrowth of the hodgepodge and complex nature of the underlaying
operating systems and toolkits.  Certainly no one can fail to be impressed
by the simplicity and elegance of Plan 9 applications.  A program to open
a window and display ``hello world'' was only three lines of code -- all
direct kernel calls!  And lest one think that the Plan 9 kernel is bloated
with huge window system code, it's not.  It's only 48Kb in size!  Plan 9
benefits from a very simple, orthogonal and well though out basis.
Unfortunately for Plan 9, the memory and CPU manufacturers have so far
managed to stay ahead of the software people.

  Finally, there's the issue of acceptance.  Even if the above problems
were dealt with, would major vendors migrate to Plan 9, the Herd or some
other operating system?  Or even provide one as a reasonably supported
alternative?  The issue benefit will be the crucial element.  A contender
to Windows/NT and UNIX will have to be able to do things vendors and
customers care about that neither Windows/NT or UNIX can do and/or can do
as well.  Certainly UNIX has proved that it can be hacked on to handle
virtually any applications ... at the expense of increasing complexity,
memory and CPU.  It looks like real-time multimedia will be the next big
hack into everyone's kernels.  But while UNIX seems to be infinitely
hackable, it's getting damnably difficult to use these new hacks that are
piled on top of one another.  Who knows, maybe Plan 9 will win in the end
simply because people will be able to understand it!

Casey

